  "texts": [
    "This suggests the following decoupling of the twisted harmonic-Einstein equation:(1) solve for c and h such that h: ( B, c) → (G/K, g sym) is weakly conformal, harmonic and ρ-equivariant;(2) solve the base equation (20b) within the conformal class c.In fact, given a conformal structure on B 2, the existence of a ρ-equivariant harmonic map can be characterised purely in terms of ρ ∈ Hom(π 1 (B), G): Theorem 4.2 (Corlette, Donaldson, Labourie, [Cor88,Don87,Lab91]).",
    "Given ρ ∈ Hom(π 1 (B), G), there exists a ρ-equivariant harmonic map h c: ( B, c) → (G/K, g sym) if and only if ρ is reductive.",
    "Moreover, h c is unique up to left multiplication by elements g ∈ G that centralise ρ(π 1 (B)).A representation ρ ∈ Hom(π 1 (B), G) is called reductive if Ad •ρ ∈ Hom(π 1 (B), Gl(𝔤)) decomposes as a sum of irreducible representations.",
    "If G is algebraic, this is equivalent to the Zariski closure of ρ(π 1 (B)) ≤ G being reductive.",
    "We denote the set of reductive representations by Hom red (π 1 (B), G)."
  ],
